  <static seed="1310" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalFunctions/reduceRationalFunction40.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the function formula, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ G(x) = {\frac{5x^{3}+x^{2}}{5x^{3}-14x^{2}-3x}} }</m></p>
<p>Reduced <m>G(x)=</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{x}{x-3}, x\ne -0.2\hbox{ and }x\ne 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cancel common factors.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   G(x) \amp = {\frac{5x^{3}+x^{2}}{5x^{3}-14x^{2}-3x}} \\
                 \amp = \frac{{x^{2}\mathopen{}\left(5x+1\right)}}{{x\mathopen{}\left(5x^{2}-14x-3\right)}} \\
                 \amp = \frac{{x^{2}\mathopen{}\left(5x+1\right)}}{{x\mathopen{}\left(5x+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(x-3\right)}} \\
                 \amp = {\frac{x}{x-3}, x\ne -0.2\hbox{ and }x\ne 0}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The expression <m>x(5x+1)</m> was canceled. To find what values would cause the crossed out expression to be <m>0</m>, we solve the equation:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   x(5x+1) \amp = 0 \\
   x = 0 \amp \text{ or } 5x+1=0 \\
   x = 0 \amp \text{ or } 5x=-1 \\
   x = 0 \amp \text{ or } x= {-{\frac{1}{5}}} \\
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The domain condition lost during the reduction is <m>x \ne {-{\frac{1}{5}}\; and \;0}</m>.</p>
</solution>
